{"title_page": "Frank Baldwin", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Major General Frank Dwight Baldwin\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1842|6|26}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1923|4|22|1842|6|26}}\n|birth_place= [[Manchester, Michigan]]\n|death_place= [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Frank Baldwin Brady-Handy oval.png\n|caption= Frank D. Baldwin\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]<br />[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= {{army|USA}}<br />[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1861, 1862\u20131865, 1866\u20131906\n|rank= [[File:Union Army major general rank insignia.svg|35px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|commands=[[27th U.S. Infantry|27th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]\n|unit= {{flagicon|Michigan}} [[19th Regiment Michigan Volunteer Infantry]]<br />[[19th U.S. Infantry|19th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]<br />[[5th U.S. Infantry|5th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]<br />[[4th U.S. Infantry|4th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]\n|battles= [[American Civil War]]<br />[[Indian Wars]]<br />[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br/>[[World War I]]\n|awards= [[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|30 px]] [[Medal of Honor]] (2)\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Frank Dwight Baldwin''' (June 26, 1842 \u2013 April 22, 1923), a native of [[Constantine, Michigan]], and born in [[Manchester, Michigan]], is one of only 19 servicemen to receive the [[Medal of Honor]] twice.  Baldwin received his first award for his actions during the Atlanta Campaign where he led his company in battle at Peachtree Creek and captured two commissioned officers in the [[American Civil War]]. He received his second for conspicuous bravery in 1874 during the [[Indian Wars]]. Baldwin holds the distinction of being the first recipient of the Medal of Honor in different conflicts.{{cn|date=April 2017}} He also fought in the [[Philippines]] during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] and rose to the rank of major general before retiring.\n\n==Life and career==\nBaldwin served in the Civil War in the [[19th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|19th Michigan Infantry]], initially as a first lieutenant,<ref name=TSHA>{{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fba43 |title=Baldwin, Francis Leonard Dwight (1842-1923) |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]}}</ref> fighting in all his regiment's battles from 1862 to 1865. In 1864, then-Captain Baldwin participated in General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]]'s famous [[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]], and on July 20 of that year distinguished himself at the [[Battle of Peachtree Creek]], earning his first Medal of Honor.<ref name=TSHA/>\n\nAfter the war, he became a student at [[Hillsdale College]], but upon the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|postbellum]] reorganization of the [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]], he joined the 19th United States Regular Infantry as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] in 1866.<ref name=Hillsdale>{{cite web |url=http://cdm15054.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/landingpage/collection/p16270coll4 |title=Major General Frank D. Baldwin Collection |publisher=Archives and Special Collections, [[Hillsdale College]]}}</ref> He was eventually assigned to the [[5th U.S. Infantry]], with whom he fought in the various frontier conflicts with the Indians.  He served with distinction under General [[Nelson A. Miles]] as chief of scouts during campaigns against [[Sitting Bull]] and [[Crazy Horse]].\n\nOn November 8, 1874, while commanding a scout company on escort duty, he led a surprise attack on the camp of [[Grey Beard]], rescuing two young sisters whose parents and brothers had been killed by another Indian band. He was awarded his second Medal of Honor for this action against a larger force in a strong defensive position. \n\nHis actions in an attack on an Indian village on the Red River in [[Montana]] on December 18, 1876, earned him a [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] of [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], U.S. Regular Army (awarded on February 27, 1890).\n\nBaldwin also served in the Philippines during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. He was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], U.S. Regular Army on June 9, 1902, and he retired in 1906.  In 1915, he was advanced to [[Major general (United States)|major general]] on the Army's retired list.\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Baldwin served as Adjutant General of the Colorado National Guard; appointed to the post in 1917, he served until retiring again in 1919. \n\nOn January 10, 1867, he married Alice Blackwood.<ref name=TSHA/><ref name=Hillsdale/> They had one daughter, Juanita.<ref name=Hillsdale/>\n\nHe died in [[Denver, Colorado]] on April 22, 1923, and was buried with full military honors in Section 3 of [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patterson|first1=Michael Robert|title=Frank Dwight Baldwin, Major General, United States Army|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm|website=www.arlingtoncemetery.net|accessdate=4 May 2018|ref=ArlCemNet|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628022226/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm|archivedate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nGeneral Baldwin belonged to numerous fraternal, military and social organizations which included the following:\n* Siloam Lodge, No. 35, [[Freemasonry|A. F. & A. M.]], at Constantine, Michigan (1863)\n* Veteran Companion, [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]], Colorado Commandery (1892)\n* [[Order of the Indian Wars of the United States]], National Commandery at Washington, D. C. (1897)\n* Veteran Companion of the [[Military Order of Foreign Wars]], Colorado Commandery (1903)\n* Honorary member of General Henry W. Lawton Camp No. 1, [[United Spanish War Veterans]] (1905)\n* [[Army & Navy Club]] of Washington, D. C. (1913)\n* [[National Geographic Society]] at Washington, D. C. (1916)\n* Honorary member of the Denver Club (1903)\n* Commercial Club of Albuquerque, New Mexico (1903)\n* Yavapai Club of [[Prescott, Arizona]] (1903)\n\n==Legacy==\nHis wife, Alice Blackwood Baldwin, honored the general's war contributions by compiling and editing the memoirs of her late husband in 1929. Along with General Baldwin, three other two-time Medal of Honor recipients are interred in [[Arlington National Cemetery]] (Navy Lieutenant Commander [[John C. McCloy]], Marine Major [[Louis Cukela]], and Marine Corporal [[John H. Pruitt|John Henry Pruitt]]).\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Viewing Hostile Indian Camp crop.jpg|thumb|left|Baldwin (right) with [[Buffalo Bill]] in 1891]]\n\n===First Medal of Honor===\nRank and organization: Captain, Company D, 19th Michigan Infantry. Place and date: At [[Battle of Peachtree Creek|Peachtree Creek, Georgia]], July 20, 1864.<ref>U.S. Congress, \"General Staff Corps and Medals of Honor,\" ''1st session of the 66th Congress, Senate Documents'', vol. 14, (Washington: Government Printing Office, 1919), 384.</ref>\nCitation: \"Led his company in a countercharge at Peach Tree Creek, Ga., 20 July 1864, under a galling fire ahead of his own men, and singly entered the enemy's line, capturing and bringing back 2 commissioned officers, fully armed, besides a guidon of a Georgia regiment.\"\nDate of issue: December 3, 1891.\n\n===Second Medal of Honor===\n[[File:Grey Beards Band, Frank Baldwin's Charge on. McWellan's Creek, Texas, Nov. 8.1874 (Cheyenne). - NARA - 533046.tif|thumb|300px|right|Frank Baldwin's charge on [[Grey Beard]]'s Band, [[McClellan Creek National Grassland|McClellan's Creek]], Texas, November 8, 1874]]\nRank and organization: First Lieutenant, 5th U.S. Infantry.\nPlace and date: At [[McClellan Creek National Grassland|McClellan's Creek]], [[Texas]], November 8, 1874.\nCitation: \"Rescued, with 2 companies, [[Mochi (Cheyenne)#German family massacre|2 white girls]] by a voluntary attack upon Indians whose superior numbers and strong position would have warranted delay for reinforcements, but which delay would have permitted the Indians to escape and kill their captives.\"\nDate of issue: November 27, 1894.<ref>U.S. Congress, \"General Staff Corps and Medals of Honor,\" ''1st session of the 66th Congress, Senate Documents'', vol. 14, (Washington: Government Printing Office, 1919), 457.</ref>\n\n===Other awards===\n*[[Civil War Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Indian Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Spanish Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Philippine Campaign Medal]]\n\n===Veteran's Hall of Fame===\nInducted into the [[Hillsdale County, Michigan]] Veteran's Hall of Fame in 2004 for his distinguished service in the American Civil War. Hall of Fame inductee 016, Civil War inductee 004.\n\n==Dates of rank==\n*Second lieutenant, Michigan Horse Guards - 19 September 1861\n*Mustered out of service - 22 November 1861\n*First lieutenant, 19th Michigan Infantry - 12 August 1862\n*Captain, 19th Michigan Infantry - 23 January 1864\n*Mustered out - 10 June 1865\n*Second lieutenant, 19th Infantry - 23 February 1866\n*First lieutenant, 19th Infantry - 10 May 1866\n*Captain, 5th Infantry - 27 March 1879\n*Brevet major - 27 February 1890\n*Major, 5th Infantry - 26 April 1898 \n*Lieutenant colonel, Inspector General, Volunteers - 20 June 1898\n*Discharged from Volunteers - 12 May 1899\n*Lieutenant colonel, 4th Infantry - 18 December 1899\n*Colonel, 27th Infantry - 26 July 1901 \n*Brigadier general, United States Army - 2 June 1902\n*Retired - 26 June 1906 <ref>Official Register of Commissioned Officers of the United States Army. 1910. pg. 473.</ref>\n*Major general, United States Army, Retired - 4 March 1915 <ref>Official Register of Commissioned Officers of the United States Army. 1923. pg. 1042.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Frank D. Baldwin}}\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n* [[List of Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F#B|List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/moh/citations_1862_cwa/baldwin_frank.html |title=homeofheroes.com: Baldwin, Frank D.}}\n* {{cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm |title=Arlington National Cemetery: Frank Dwight Baldwin}}\n* {{Find a Grave|9038|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=December 19, 2007}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140903082255/http://files.usgwarchives.org/co/denver/bios/baldwin297nbs.txt Biography from Denver County Archives]\n* Steinbach, Robert H. ''A Long March: The Lives of Frank and Alice Baldwin''. University of Texas Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-292-74185-0}}\n*Marquis Who's Who, Inc. ''Who Was Who in American History, the Military''. Chicago: Marquis Who's Who, 1975. {{ISBN|0837932017}} {{OCLC|657162692}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldwin, Frank}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:People of Michigan in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of the Great Sioux War of 1876]]\n[[Category:Hamilton College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Constantine, Michigan]]\n[[Category:American Indian Wars recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Double Recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Major General Frank Dwight Baldwin\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1842|6|26}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1923|4|22|1842|6|26}}\n|birth_place= [[Manchester, Michigan]]\n|death_place= [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Frank Baldwin Brady-Handy oval.png\n|caption= Frank D. Baldwin\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]<br />[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= {{army|USA}}<br />[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1861, 1862\u20131865, 1866\u20131906\n|rank= [[File:Union Army major general rank insignia.svg|35px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|commands=[[27th U.S. Infantry|27th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]\n|unit= [[19th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|19th Michigan Infantry Regiment]]<br />[[19th U.S. Infantry|19th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]<br />[[5th U.S. Infantry|5th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]<br />[[4th U.S. Infantry|4th U.S. Infantry Regiment]]\n|battles= [[American Civil War]]<br />[[Indian Wars]]<br />[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br/>[[World War I]]\n|awards= [[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|30 px]] [[Medal of Honor]] (2)\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Frank Dwight Baldwin''' (June 26, 1842 \u2013 April 22, 1923), a native of [[Constantine, Michigan]], and born in [[Manchester, Michigan]], is one of only 19 servicemen to receive the [[Medal of Honor]] twice.  Baldwin received his first award for his actions during the Atlanta Campaign where he led his company in battle at Peachtree Creek and captured two commissioned officers in the [[American Civil War]]. He received his second for conspicuous bravery in 1874 during the [[Indian Wars]]. Baldwin holds the distinction of being the first recipient of the Medal of Honor in different conflicts.{{cn|date=April 2017}} He also fought in the [[Philippines]] during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] and rose to the rank of major general before retiring.\n\n==Life and career==\nBaldwin served in the Civil War in the [[19th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|19th Michigan Infantry]], initially as a first lieutenant,<ref name=TSHA>{{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fba43 |title=Baldwin, Francis Leonard Dwight (1842-1923) |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]}}</ref> fighting in all his regiment's battles from 1862 to 1865. In 1864, then-Captain Baldwin participated in General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]]'s famous [[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]], and on July 20 of that year distinguished himself at the [[Battle of Peachtree Creek]], earning his first Medal of Honor.<ref name=TSHA/>\n\nAfter the war, he became a student at [[Hillsdale College]], but upon the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|postbellum]] reorganization of the [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]], he joined the 19th United States Regular Infantry as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] in 1866.<ref name=Hillsdale>{{cite web |url=http://cdm15054.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/landingpage/collection/p16270coll4 |title=Major General Frank D. Baldwin Collection |publisher=Archives and Special Collections, [[Hillsdale College]]}}</ref> He was eventually assigned to the [[5th U.S. Infantry]], with whom he fought in the various frontier conflicts with the Indians.  He served with distinction under General [[Nelson A. Miles]] as chief of scouts during campaigns against [[Sitting Bull]] and [[Crazy Horse]].\n\nOn November 8, 1874, while commanding a scout company on escort duty, he led a surprise attack on the camp of [[Grey Beard]], rescuing two young sisters whose parents and brothers had been killed by another Indian band. He was awarded his second Medal of Honor for this action against a larger force in a strong defensive position. \n\nHis actions in an attack on an Indian village on the Red River in [[Montana]] on December 18, 1876, earned him a [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] of [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], U.S. Regular Army (awarded on February 27, 1890).\n\nBaldwin also served in the Philippines during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. He was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], U.S. Regular Army on June 9, 1902, and he retired in 1906.  In 1915, he was advanced to [[Major general (United States)|major general]] on the Army's retired list.\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Baldwin served as Adjutant General of the Colorado National Guard; appointed to the post in 1917, he served until retiring again in 1919. \n\nOn January 10, 1867, he married Alice Blackwood.<ref name=TSHA/><ref name=Hillsdale/> They had one daughter, Juanita.<ref name=Hillsdale/>\n\nHe died in [[Denver, Colorado]] on April 22, 1923, and was buried with full military honors in Section 3 of [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patterson|first1=Michael Robert|title=Frank Dwight Baldwin, Major General, United States Army|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm|website=www.arlingtoncemetery.net|accessdate=4 May 2018|ref=ArlCemNet|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628022226/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm|archivedate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nGeneral Baldwin belonged to numerous fraternal, military and social organizations which included the following:\n* Siloam Lodge, No. 35, [[Freemasonry|A. F. & A. M.]], at Constantine, Michigan (1863)\n* Veteran Companion, [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]], Colorado Commandery (1892)\n* [[Order of the Indian Wars of the United States]], National Commandery at Washington, D. C. (1897)\n* Veteran Companion of the [[Military Order of Foreign Wars]], Colorado Commandery (1903)\n* Honorary member of General Henry W. Lawton Camp No. 1, [[United Spanish War Veterans]] (1905)\n* [[Army & Navy Club]] of Washington, D. C. (1913)\n* [[National Geographic Society]] at Washington, D. C. (1916)\n* Honorary member of the Denver Club (1903)\n* Commercial Club of Albuquerque, New Mexico (1903)\n* Yavapai Club of [[Prescott, Arizona]] (1903)\n\n==Legacy==\nHis wife, Alice Blackwood Baldwin, honored the general's war contributions by compiling and editing the memoirs of her late husband in 1929. Along with General Baldwin, three other two-time Medal of Honor recipients are interred in [[Arlington National Cemetery]] (Navy Lieutenant Commander [[John C. McCloy]], Marine Major [[Louis Cukela]], and Marine Corporal [[John H. Pruitt|John Henry Pruitt]]).\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Viewing Hostile Indian Camp crop.jpg|thumb|left|Baldwin (right) with [[Buffalo Bill]] in 1891]]\n\n===First Medal of Honor===\nRank and organization: Captain, Company D, 19th Michigan Infantry. Place and date: At [[Battle of Peachtree Creek|Peachtree Creek, Georgia]], July 20, 1864.<ref>U.S. Congress, \"General Staff Corps and Medals of Honor,\" ''1st session of the 66th Congress, Senate Documents'', vol. 14, (Washington: Government Printing Office, 1919), 384.</ref>\nCitation: \"Led his company in a countercharge at Peach Tree Creek, Ga., 20 July 1864, under a galling fire ahead of his own men, and singly entered the enemy's line, capturing and bringing back 2 commissioned officers, fully armed, besides a guidon of a Georgia regiment.\"\nDate of issue: December 3, 1891.\n\n===Second Medal of Honor===\n[[File:Grey Beards Band, Frank Baldwin's Charge on. McWellan's Creek, Texas, Nov. 8.1874 (Cheyenne). - NARA - 533046.tif|thumb|300px|right|Frank Baldwin's charge on [[Grey Beard]]'s Band, [[McClellan Creek National Grassland|McClellan's Creek]], Texas, November 8, 1874]]\nRank and organization: First Lieutenant, 5th U.S. Infantry.\nPlace and date: At [[McClellan Creek National Grassland|McClellan's Creek]], [[Texas]], November 8, 1874.\nCitation: \"Rescued, with 2 companies, [[Mochi (Cheyenne)#German family massacre|2 white girls]] by a voluntary attack upon Indians whose superior numbers and strong position would have warranted delay for reinforcements, but which delay would have permitted the Indians to escape and kill their captives.\"\nDate of issue: November 27, 1894.<ref>U.S. Congress, \"General Staff Corps and Medals of Honor,\" ''1st session of the 66th Congress, Senate Documents'', vol. 14, (Washington: Government Printing Office, 1919), 457.</ref>\n\n===Other awards===\n*[[Civil War Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Indian Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Spanish Campaign Medal]]\n*[[Philippine Campaign Medal]]\n\n===Veteran's Hall of Fame===\nInducted into the [[Hillsdale County, Michigan]] Veteran's Hall of Fame in 2004 for his distinguished service in the American Civil War. Hall of Fame inductee 016, Civil War inductee 004.\n\n==Dates of rank==\n*Second lieutenant, Michigan Horse Guards - 19 September 1861\n*Mustered out of service - 22 November 1861\n*First lieutenant, 19th Michigan Infantry - 12 August 1862\n*Captain, 19th Michigan Infantry - 23 January 1864\n*Mustered out - 10 June 1865\n*Second lieutenant, 19th Infantry - 23 February 1866\n*First lieutenant, 19th Infantry - 10 May 1866\n*Captain, 5th Infantry - 27 March 1879\n*Brevet major - 27 February 1890\n*Major, 5th Infantry - 26 April 1898 \n*Lieutenant colonel, Inspector General, Volunteers - 20 June 1898\n*Discharged from Volunteers - 12 May 1899\n*Lieutenant colonel, 4th Infantry - 18 December 1899\n*Colonel, 27th Infantry - 26 July 1901 \n*Brigadier general, United States Army - 2 June 1902\n*Retired - 26 June 1906 <ref>Official Register of Commissioned Officers of the United States Army. 1910. pg. 473.</ref>\n*Major general, United States Army, Retired - 4 March 1915 <ref>Official Register of Commissioned Officers of the United States Army. 1923. pg. 1042.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Frank D. Baldwin}}\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n* [[List of Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F#B|List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/moh/citations_1862_cwa/baldwin_frank.html |title=homeofheroes.com: Baldwin, Frank D.}}\n* {{cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/fdbaldwi.htm |title=Arlington National Cemetery: Frank Dwight Baldwin}}\n* {{Find a Grave|9038|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=December 19, 2007}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140903082255/http://files.usgwarchives.org/co/denver/bios/baldwin297nbs.txt Biography from Denver County Archives]\n* Steinbach, Robert H. ''A Long March: The Lives of Frank and Alice Baldwin''. University of Texas Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-292-74185-0}}\n*Marquis Who's Who, Inc. ''Who Was Who in American History, the Military''. Chicago: Marquis Who's Who, 1975. {{ISBN|0837932017}} {{OCLC|657162692}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldwin, Frank}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:People of Michigan in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of the Great Sioux War of 1876]]\n[[Category:Hamilton College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Constantine, Michigan]]\n[[Category:American Indian Wars recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Double Recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Baldwin"}
{"title_page": "Maha Al-Saati", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maha Al-Saati<br><big>\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a</big>\n| image              = Maha Al-Saati.png\n| birth_place        = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| education          = King Faisal University (B.A, M.A); Simon Fraser University (PhD)\n| alma_mater         = Simon Fraser University\n| occupation         = Independent Filmmaker, University Professor\n| years_active       = 2016\u2013present\n| Genre              = Experimental Narrative, Avant-garde\n}}\n\n'''Maha Al-Saati''' (also known as '''Maha Alsaati''', '''Maha Zeini Al-Saati''', [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: [[:ar:\u0645\u0647\u0627_\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a|\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a]]) is a [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] female filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and university professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.edu.sa/en/colleges/college-of-design/faculty/dr-maha-al-saati|title=Dr. Maha Al-Saati {{!}} Imam Abdulrahman Bin Faisal University|website=www.iau.edu.sa|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?hl=en&lr=&id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=maha+al-saati+protagonist&ots=wXoMqhB1uD&sig=kTJk98HExkxXU4A4XwYp5qymoSE&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20protagonist&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref> who has taught both in Vancouver, Canada and Saudi Arabia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.edu.sa/en/colleges/college-of-design/faculty/dr-maha-al-saati|title=Dr. Maha Al-Saati {{!}} Imam Abdulrahman Bin Faisal University|website=www.iau.edu.sa|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>. ''\"Director Maha Alsaati, known for shorts that explore femininity and gender roles in Arab cultures\"'', [[Variety (magazine)]] says<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. Her filmmaking style has been described as [[Avant-garde]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, experimental<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, and heavily inspired by the aesthetics of 90s [[MTV]] music videos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. She is of mixed [[Arabs|Arab]] and [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] ancestry<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nasr|first=Magy Seif El|last2=Al-Saati|first2=Maha|last3=Niedenthal|first3=Simon|last4=Milam|first4=David|date=2008-11-11|title=Assassin\u2019s Creed: A Multi-Cultural Read|url=http://journals.sfu.ca/loading/index.php/loading/article/view/51|journal=Loading...|language=en|volume=2|issue=3|issn=1923-2691}}</ref>.\n\n== Filmmaking Career ==\nAl-Saati is interested in exploring issues of gender, religion and Arab social norms in her films <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Her previous short films include:[[File:Fantastic-fest-fear-audibly-maha-alsaati-qa-sep-2017.png|thumb|262x262px|Q&A with Maha Al-Saati after the screening of \"Fear: Audibly\" at Fantastic Fest Sep 26, 2017]]\n=== Fear: Audibly (2017) ===\nAl-Saati started her filmmaking career with short films such as ''\"Fear: Audibly\" (2017),'' which screened at [[Fantastic Fest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasticfest.com//films/fear-audibly|title=FEAR: AUDIBLY|website=Fantastic Fest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriteaboutcomics.com/2017/09/fantastic-shorts-by-women-at-fantastic-fest/|title=Fantastic Shorts by Women at Fantastic Fest|date=2017-09-30|website=WWAC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and the [[Arab World Institute]]'s Arab Cinema Festival in Paris under the French title ''\"La Peur: sonore\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imarabe.org/fr/cinema/la-peur-sonore|title=La Peur : sonore|date=2018-06-11|website=Institut du monde arabe|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. The film has set her style as \"sound-dependant\", inspired by ''\"growing up in Saudi Arabia in the \u201880s and \u201890s\" as there was an Islamic restriction on visuals and a dependency on audio. \"Preachers used cassette tapes a lot, so a lot of the things that we hear, the stories, they\u2019re always sound based. The narrative is always non-visual. In the Islamic tradition, even the ending of time was signaled by the trumpet of doom.\"'' The film is also inspired by [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]] [[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]], who speaks about the ''\"disembodiment of sound.. it\u2019s just floating ... It\u2019s kind of unnatural, like a ghost.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The film's sountrack includes the \"Modus Futurus Posterus Machina\" album by LA-based composer [[Gavin Gamboa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2936950/|title=Gavin Gamboa|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Slamdance-20190126-Maa-Alsaati-Hair-story-of-grass.png|thumb|262x262px|Q&A with Maha Al-Saati (writer, director) and Gavin Gamboa (composer) after the screening of \"Hair: The Story of Grass\" at Slamdance Jan 26, 2019.]]\n=== Hair: The Story of Grass (2018) ===\nAl-Saati's short film ''\"Hair: The Story of Grass\" (2018)\",'' explores the topic of body hair and beauty standards in the Arab World<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rdvcanada.ca/en/product/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story of Grass {{!}} Canadian Audiovisual Production|website=RDVCanada.ca|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, and has screened at [[Fantastic Fest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasticfest.com//films/hair-the-story-of-grass|title=HAIR: THE STORY OF GRASS|website=Fantastic Fest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2018/09/05/announcing-fantastic-fests-2018-shorts-programming|title=Announcing Fantastic Fest\u2019s 2018 Shorts Programming|last=Monson|first=Leigh|date=2018-09-05|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, [[Slamdance Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slamdance2019.eventive.org/schedule/5c1c0bd934d66c00225a9ea6|title=Hair: The Story of Grass|last=|first=|date=|website=Slamdance 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/steven-soderbergh-to-receive-2019-founders-award-at-slamdance-festival/|title=Steven Soderbergh to Receive Founders Award at Slamdance Festival|date=2018-12-11|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> , The Arab Film Festival of the [[Arab American National Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aanmfilmfest.org/schedule/short-doc-block-pwwbf|title=Outside-The-Box Short Films|website=Arab Film Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>, New Filmmakers LA Monthly Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newfilmmakersla.com/events/event/monthly-film-festival-july-27th-2019/|title=Monthly Film Festival \u2013 July 27th, 2019|website=LA Film Festival NewFilmmakers Los Angeles|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> and the [[Red Sea International Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redseafilmfest.com/film?id=79|title=Hair: The Story of Grass - RedSeaFF2020|last=Apps|first=77|website=www.redseafilmfest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. It is described by [[Film Threat]] as \"Loosely based on fairy tales and children\u2019s stories\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story Of Grass {{!}} Film Threat|last=says|first=Hair: The Story of Grass-maha al-saati x films|date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and ''\"similar to the style of [[Spike Lee]], Director/writer Maha Al-Saati doesn\u2019t take sides on any issue. She merely presents a story that highlights an aspect of her culture. She isn\u2019t there to tell us how we\u2019re supposed to feel about it.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story Of Grass {{!}} Film Threat|last=says|first=Hair: The Story of Grass-maha al-saati x films|date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Her background in architecture plays an important role in shaping the cinematic spaces she creates. It also mocks the Arab traditions of bodyhair removals, assigning different body hair codes that define masculinity and femininity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The film includes soundtracks by [[Gavin Gamboa]] along with other sound artists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2936950/|title=Gavin Gamboa|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Zeina-Nassereddine-NFMLA-Academy-Dec-2019.jpg|alt=Zeina Nassereddine (Vocalist) speaks about Cycle of Apples after its screening at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences at New Filmmakers LA Middle Eastern Cinema event in partnership with the Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI), 14 Dec 2019|thumb|Zeina Nassereddine (Vocalist) speaks about \"Cycle of Apples\" after its screening at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences at New Filmmakers LA Middle Eastern Cinema event in partnership with the Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI), 14 Dec 2019|261x261px]]\n=== Cycle of Apples (2019) ===\nHer short film ''\"Cycle of Apples\" (2019)'' screened at New Filmmakers LA Monthly Film festival, which was hosted by The [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] in partnership with Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newfilmmakersla.com/events/event/monthly-film-festival-december-14th-2019/|title=Monthly Film Festival \u2013 December 14th, 2019|website=LA Film Festival NewFilmmakers Los Angeles|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> in addition to the 14th Twin Cities Mizna Arab Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miznablog.org/arabfilmfest19/2019/sisters-mothers-friends-lovers/|title=Mizna Arab Film Festival 2019 {{!}} Sisters, Mothers, Friends, Lovers: A Collection of Shorts|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>, [[Beirut International Women Film Festival]], [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival, and the [[Oaxaca FilmFest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oaxacafilmfest.com/p/cycle-of-apples|website=www.oaxacafilmfest.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. The film is a collaboration with American electronic opera composer [[Alice Shields]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and Arab-American Vocalist and opera singer Zeina Nassereddine<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mFL4qwtXUMU&t=1s|title=Stage 5 {{!}} Zeina Nasseredine|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The Soundtrack includes Shields'  Agnus Dei (1992), Criseyde's Dream (2008), Quartet for Piano and Percussion (2016), The River of Memory for trombone & electronics (2016). The official instagram page of [[Toronto International Film Festival]] describes the film as \"..''a fable of women\u2019s suffering, inspired by Eve\u2019s \u201cforbidden apple\u201d in the Garden of Eden, and Snow White. Filmed in Saudi Arabia, it could be set anywhere in the world today, with its urgent and all-too-timely message about the cycle of abuse against women \u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BlIybkoHmUK/|title=TIFF on Instagram: \u201cMaha Al-Saati (@elosnest)\u2019s brilliant EAT ME: CYCLE OF APPLES is a fable of women\u2019s suffering, inspired by Eve\u2019s \u201cforbidden apple\u201d in the\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.\n\n=== A Trip to Disney (Work in progress) ===\nAl-Saati's feature film project \"A Trip to Disney\" is in development with the Red Sea Film Lodge (part of Saudi Arabia's [[Red Sea International Film Festival]]), in partnership with Italy's [[TorinoFilmLab]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.torinofilmlab.it/news/640-announcing-the-12-selected-projects-for-the-red-sea-lodge-2019|title=Announcing the 12 selected projects for the Red Sea Lodge 2019! {{!}} TorinoFilmLab|website=www.torinofilmlab.it|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>''.'' She is one of the female directors that account for one-third of the 12 selected for the Red Sea Lodge, the festival said<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/saudis-red-sea-international-film-festival-unveils-debut-lab-selection/5143374.article|title=Saudi's Red Sea International Film Festival unveils debut lab selection|last=Goodfellow2019-10-01T15:55:00+01:00|first=Melanie|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. ''\"The new project is about a Saudi woman who, abandoned by her lover, travels from Saudi Arabia to Florida. \u201cFinding herself in the Disney empire,\u201d presumably at Disney World in Orlando, the film\u2019s protagonist \u201cdiscovers she is not his princess,\u201d reads the synopsis. Saudi women up until last month were not allowed to travel abroad without permission from a male \u201cguardian\u201d'', [[Variety (magazine)]] says<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>.\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Film Title\n!Arabic Title\n!Year\n!Type\n!Screenings\n!Nominations\n|-\n|Elo's Nest\n|\u0639\u0634 \u0625\u064a\u0644\u0648\n|2016\n|short film\n|The 3rd Saudi Film Festival, [[Bare Bones International Film Festival]]\n|\n|-\n|Fear: Audibly\n|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0648\u0641: \u0635\u0648\u062a\u064a\u0627\n|2017\n|short film\n|[[Fantastic Fest]], The Arab Cinema Festival at the [[Arab World Institute]] in Paris, The 4th Saudi Film Festival\n|\n|-\n|Hair: The Story of Grass\n|\u0634\u0639\u0631: \u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0639\u0634\u0628\n|2018\n|short film\n|[[Fantastic Fest]], [[Slamdance Film Festival]], [[HollyShorts Film Festival]], [[Red Sea International Film Festival]], The Arab Film Festival of the [[Arab American National Museum]], The 5th Saudi Film Festival, [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival, Casablana Film Festival.\n|Nominated for the NewFilmmakers Los Angeles 2020 Best of NFMLA Awards in the Best International Short Film, Drama category\n|-\n|E-pidemic\n|\u0622\u0641\u0629 \u0625\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0631\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0629\n|2018\n|short film\n|[[Middle East Broadcasting Center]] Channel / AramTV - Qomrah 3 Show\n|\n|-\n|Cycle of Apples\n|\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u062a\u0641\u0627\u062d\n|2019\n|short film\n|The14th Mizna Twin Cities Arab Film Festival, 10th Oaxaca FilmFest, 25th SPE Media Festival 2020, [[Beirut International Women Film Festival]] (BWFF), The New Filmmakers LA Film festival hosted by The [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]],  [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival.\n|\n|-\n|A Trip to Disney (working title)\n|\u0631\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u062f\u064a\u0632\u0646\u064a\n|In-Development\n|feature\n|In-Development with The [[Red Sea International Film Festival]], in partnership with Italy's [[TorinoFilmLab]]<ref name=\":0\" />''.'' \n|\n|}\n\n== Research ==\nAl-Saati holds a Bachelors degree in Interior Design and a Masters degree in Architecture from King Faisal University, Saudi Arabia<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA336&lpg=PA336&dq=maha+al-saati+king+faisal+university&source=bl&ots=wXoRjpI-BJ&sig=ACfU3U1p-09x0U5pX6Hhp0JO3FSHGROGlw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjC_4KTkfToAhX4SBUIHV0nCY8Q6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20king%20faisal%20university&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref>.  She also has a PhD in Interactive Arts and Technology, from [[Simon Fraser University]] (SFU), [[Surrey, British Columbia]], [[Canada]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA282&lpg=PA282&dq=maha+zeini+al-saati&source=bl&ots=EO8_LSmG5c&sig=ACfU3U1P-X0pBuyt6e8pu5_k0IvTiyb_bA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsqoT_vfLnAhVfRhUIHV6ACMkQ6AEwCXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20zeini%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis|title=The architectural image: space, movement and myth|url=https://summit.sfu.ca/item/13638|publisher=Communication, Art & Technology: School of Interactive Arts and Technology|date=2013-07-22|degree=Thesis|language=en|first=Maha Zeini|last=Al-Saati}}</ref>. Her PhD thesis is titled: ''\"The Architectural Image: Space, Movement and Myth\"'' (2013), which was supervised by Dr. [[Robert Woodbury (athlete)|Robert Woodbury]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Saati|first=Maha Zeini|title=The Architectural Image: Space, Movement and Myth|url=https://www.academia.edu/7577363/The_Architectural_Image_Space_Movement_and_Myth|journal=PhD Thesis, The School of Interactive Arts and Technology, Simon Fraser University (SFU), Canada.|language=en}}</ref>, and falls within research that intersects architecture with film<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00a0Al-Saati, Maha Zeini; David Botta and Robert Woodbury|first=|date=|title=Moving in filmic spaces: Relating camera movements to spatial archetypes in architectural animations|url=http://papers.cumincad.org/cgi-bin/works/paper/caadria2012_013|journal=Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on Computer Aided Architectural Design Research in Asia|volume=|pages=Chennai 25-28 April 2012|via=Chennai 25-28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Saati|first=Maha Zeini; David Botta and Robert Woodbury|date=2012|title=Architects on architectural film and animation|url=http://papers.cumincad.org/cgi-bin/works/Show?caadria2012_021|journal=Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on Computer Aided Architectural Design Research in Asia / Chennai 25-28 April 2012, pp. 637\u2013646|publisher=CUMINCAD}}</ref>. She is also a researcher who has written about the intersection of media, religion and culture<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA282&lpg=PA282&dq=maha+zeini+al-saati&source=bl&ots=EO8_LSmG5c&sig=ACfU3U1P-X0pBuyt6e8pu5_k0IvTiyb_bA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsqoT_vfLnAhVfRhUIHV6ACMkQ6AEwCXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20zeini%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref> in her works: ''\u201cThe Protagonist Does Not Die Anymore: The Influence of the Death Narrative on Popular Saudi Culture\u201d''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR6&dq=maha+al-saati+Death+within+the+Text:+Social,+Philosophical+and+Aesthetic+Approaches+to+Literature,+edited+by+Adriana+Teodorescu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjR_IOF-vHnAhXMA2MBHThHAh4Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref>''; \"A Question of Relevance: Teaching with Sci-Fi and Fantasy Film in a Saudi University\"''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?hl=en&lr=&id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=maha+al-saati+protagonist&ots=wXoMqhB1uD&sig=kTJk98HExkxXU4A4XwYp5qymoSE&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20protagonist&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref>; and the journal article ''\"Assassin's Creed : A Multi-Cultural Read\"''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seif El-Nasr|first=Magy|last2=Al-Saati|first2=Maha|last3=Niedenthal|first3=Simon|last4=Milam|first4=David|date=2008|title=Assassin's Creed : A Multi-Cultural Read|url=http://muep.mau.se/handle/2043/12753|journal=Loading . . .;3|volume=2|issn=1923-2691}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Winston|first=Diane|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=MCCja27G0AAC&pg=PA241&lpg=PA241&dq=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Religion+and+the+American+News+Media+maha+al-saati&source=bl&ots=JTS1BfUQdE&sig=ACfU3U31GPn0jUDaYQ3aOw3tSyCpOR2j2g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn08azl_TnAhVz8uAKHax6A8cQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20Oxford%20Handbook%20of%20Religion%20and%20the%20American%20News%20Media%20maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of Religion and the American News Media|date=2012-09-06|publisher=OUP USA|isbn=978-0-19-539506-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Young|first=Helen|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=eCg_CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT207&dq=maha+al-saati&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSoZjQl_TnAhVFA2MBHXxmBrsQ6AEIQTAD#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=The Middle Ages in Popular Culture: Medievalism and Genre|date=2015-07-08|publisher=Cambria Press|isbn=978-1-62196-748-4|language=en}}</ref>. French author Lily Valette covers her short film Hair: The Story of Grass in her book ''\u201cDans le sens du poil arabe\" (2020) [English: In the Direction of Arab Hair]'' which compares the social attitudes towards body hair in Arab versus Western culture<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.lalibrairie.com/livres/le-poil-arabe_0-6236267_9791093315171.html|title=Livre : Dans le sens du poil arabe \u00e9crit par Maha Al-Saati et Lily Valette - Orients|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culture.leclerc/livre-u/arts-culture--societe-u/sciences-humaines-u/ethnologie-u/le-poil-arabe-9791093315171-pr|title=Dans le sens du poil arabe|last=E.Leclerc|first=Dans le sens du poil arabe-Lily Valette- 9791093315171- Espace Culturel|website=Espace Culturel E. Leclerc|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gibert.com/le-poil-arabe-11464541.html|title=Ldans le sens du poil arabe|website=www.gibert.com|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8242195}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{morecat|date=April 2020|Categories=}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Al-Saati, Maha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Arab film directors]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Canadian experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Canada-film-director-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maha Al-Saati<br><big>\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a</big>\n| image              = Maha Al-Saati.png\n| birth_place        = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| education          = King Faisal University (B.A, M.A); Simon Fraser University (PhD)\n| alma_mater         = Simon Fraser University\n| occupation         = Independent Filmmaker, University Professor\n| years_active       = 2016\u2013present\n| Genre              = Experimental Narrative, Avant-garde\n}}\n\n'''Maha Al-Saati''' (also known as '''Maha Alsaati''', '''Maha Zeini Al-Saati''', [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: [[:ar:\u0645\u0647\u0627_\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a|\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0627\u062a\u064a]]) is a [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] female filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and university professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.edu.sa/en/colleges/college-of-design/faculty/dr-maha-al-saati|title=Dr. Maha Al-Saati {{!}} Imam Abdulrahman Bin Faisal University|website=www.iau.edu.sa|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?hl=en&lr=&id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=maha+al-saati+protagonist&ots=wXoMqhB1uD&sig=kTJk98HExkxXU4A4XwYp5qymoSE&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20protagonist&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref> who has taught both in Vancouver, Canada and Saudi Arabia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.edu.sa/en/colleges/college-of-design/faculty/dr-maha-al-saati|title=Dr. Maha Al-Saati {{!}} Imam Abdulrahman Bin Faisal University|website=www.iau.edu.sa|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>. ''\"Director Maha Alsaati, known for shorts that explore femininity and gender roles in Arab cultures\"'', [[Variety (magazine)]] says<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. Her filmmaking style has been described as [[Avant-garde]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, experimental<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, and heavily inspired by the aesthetics of 90s [[MTV]] music videos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. She is of mixed [[Arabs|Arab]] and [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] ancestry<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nasr|first=Magy Seif El|last2=Al-Saati|first2=Maha|last3=Niedenthal|first3=Simon|last4=Milam|first4=David|date=2008-11-11|title=Assassin\u2019s Creed: A Multi-Cultural Read|url=http://journals.sfu.ca/loading/index.php/loading/article/view/51|journal=Loading...|language=en|volume=2|issue=3|issn=1923-2691}}</ref>.\n\n== Filmmaking Career ==\nAl-Saati is interested in exploring issues of gender, religion and Arab social norms in her films <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Her previous short films include:[[File:Fantastic-fest-fear-audibly-maha-alsaati-qa-sep-2017.png|thumb|262x262px|Q&A with Maha Al-Saati after the screening of \"Fear: Audibly\" at Fantastic Fest Sep 26, 2017]]\n=== Fear: Audibly (2017) ===\nAl-Saati started her filmmaking career with short films such as ''\"Fear: Audibly\" (2017),'' which screened at [[Fantastic Fest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasticfest.com//films/fear-audibly|title=FEAR: AUDIBLY|website=Fantastic Fest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriteaboutcomics.com/2017/09/fantastic-shorts-by-women-at-fantastic-fest/|title=Fantastic Shorts by Women at Fantastic Fest|date=2017-09-30|website=WWAC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and the [[Arab World Institute]]'s Arab Cinema Festival in Paris under the French title ''\"La Peur: sonore\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imarabe.org/fr/cinema/la-peur-sonore|title=La Peur : sonore|date=2018-06-11|website=Institut du monde arabe|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. The film has set her style as \"sound-dependant\", inspired by ''\"growing up in Saudi Arabia in the \u201880s and \u201890s\" as there was an Islamic restriction on visuals and a dependency on audio. \"Preachers used cassette tapes a lot, so a lot of the things that we hear, the stories, they\u2019re always sound based. The narrative is always non-visual. In the Islamic tradition, even the ending of time was signaled by the trumpet of doom.\"'' The film is also inspired by [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]] [[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]], who speaks about the ''\"disembodiment of sound.. it\u2019s just floating ... It\u2019s kind of unnatural, like a ghost.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/10/04/fantastic-fest-shorts-fear-audibly-and-the-mysterious-emotions-of-sound|title=Fantastic Fest Shorts: FEAR AUDIBLY And The Mysterious Emotions Of Sound|last=Adlakha|first=Siddhant|date=2017-10-04|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The film's sountrack includes the \"Modus Futurus Posterus Machina\" album by LA-based composer [[Gavin Gamboa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2936950/|title=Gavin Gamboa|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Slamdance-20190126-Maa-Alsaati-Hair-story-of-grass.png|thumb|262x262px|Q&A with Maha Al-Saati (writer, director) and Gavin Gamboa (composer) after the screening of \"Hair: The Story of Grass\" at Slamdance Jan 26, 2019.]]\n=== Hair: The Story of Grass (2018) ===\nAl-Saati's short film ''\"Hair: The Story of Grass\" (2018)\",'' explores the topic of body hair and beauty standards in the Arab World<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rdvcanada.ca/en/product/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story of Grass {{!}} Canadian Audiovisual Production|website=RDVCanada.ca|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, and has screened at [[Fantastic Fest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasticfest.com//films/hair-the-story-of-grass|title=HAIR: THE STORY OF GRASS|website=Fantastic Fest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2018/09/05/announcing-fantastic-fests-2018-shorts-programming|title=Announcing Fantastic Fest\u2019s 2018 Shorts Programming|last=Monson|first=Leigh|date=2018-09-05|website=Birth.Movies.Death.|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>, [[Slamdance Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slamdance2019.eventive.org/schedule/5c1c0bd934d66c00225a9ea6|title=Hair: The Story of Grass|last=|first=|date=|website=Slamdance 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/steven-soderbergh-to-receive-2019-founders-award-at-slamdance-festival/|title=Steven Soderbergh to Receive Founders Award at Slamdance Festival|date=2018-12-11|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> , The Arab Film Festival of the [[Arab American National Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aanmfilmfest.org/schedule/short-doc-block-pwwbf|title=Outside-The-Box Short Films|website=Arab Film Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>, New Filmmakers LA Monthly Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newfilmmakersla.com/events/event/monthly-film-festival-july-27th-2019/|title=Monthly Film Festival \u2013 July 27th, 2019|website=LA Film Festival NewFilmmakers Los Angeles|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> and the [[Red Sea International Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redseafilmfest.com/film?id=79|title=Hair: The Story of Grass - RedSeaFF2020|last=Apps|first=77|website=www.redseafilmfest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. It is described by [[Film Threat]] as \"Loosely based on fairy tales and children\u2019s stories\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story Of Grass {{!}} Film Threat|last=says|first=Hair: The Story of Grass-maha al-saati x films|date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and ''\"similar to the style of [[Spike Lee]], Director/writer Maha Al-Saati doesn\u2019t take sides on any issue. She merely presents a story that highlights an aspect of her culture. She isn\u2019t there to tell us how we\u2019re supposed to feel about it.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/hair-the-story-of-grass/|title=Hair: The Story Of Grass {{!}} Film Threat|last=says|first=Hair: The Story of Grass-maha al-saati x films|date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Her background in architecture plays an important role in shaping the cinematic spaces she creates. It also mocks the Arab traditions of bodyhair removals, assigning different body hair codes that define masculinity and femininity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kawa-news.com/en/maha-el-saati-the-fantastic-ufo-from-saudi-experimental-cinema/|title=Maha El Saati, the fantastic UFO from Saudi experimental cinema|date=2019-02-11|website=KAWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The film includes soundtracks by [[Gavin Gamboa]] along with other sound artists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2936950/|title=Gavin Gamboa|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Zeina-Nassereddine-NFMLA-Academy-Dec-2019.jpg|alt=Zeina Nassereddine (Vocalist) speaks about Cycle of Apples after its screening at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences at New Filmmakers LA Middle Eastern Cinema event in partnership with the Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI), 14 Dec 2019|thumb|Zeina Nassereddine (Vocalist) speaks about \"Cycle of Apples\" after its screening at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences at New Filmmakers LA Middle Eastern Cinema event in partnership with the Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI), 14 Dec 2019|261x261px]]\n=== Cycle of Apples (2019) ===\nHer short film ''\"Cycle of Apples\" (2019)'' screened at New Filmmakers LA Monthly Film festival, which was hosted by The [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] in partnership with Arab Film and Media Institute (AFMI)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newfilmmakersla.com/events/event/monthly-film-festival-december-14th-2019/|title=Monthly Film Festival \u2013 December 14th, 2019|website=LA Film Festival NewFilmmakers Los Angeles|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> in addition to the 14th Twin Cities Mizna Arab Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miznablog.org/arabfilmfest19/2019/sisters-mothers-friends-lovers/|title=Mizna Arab Film Festival 2019 {{!}} Sisters, Mothers, Friends, Lovers: A Collection of Shorts|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>, [[Beirut International Women Film Festival]], [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival, and the [[Oaxaca FilmFest]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oaxacafilmfest.com/p/cycle-of-apples|website=www.oaxacafilmfest.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. The film is a collaboration with American electronic opera composer [[Alice Shields]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iscm.org/catalogue/composers/shields-alice|title=Shields, Alice|last=ISCM|date=2019-07-31|website=ISCM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studio300.transy.edu/digital-media/creators/|title=Creators \u2013 Studio 300|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and Arab Vocalist Zeina Nassereddine<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mFL4qwtXUMU&t=1s|title=Stage 5 {{!}} Zeina Nasseredine|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The Soundtrack includes Shields'  Agnus Dei (1992), Criseyde's Dream (2008), Quartet for Piano and Percussion (2016), The River of Memory for trombone & electronics (2016). The official instagram page of [[Toronto International Film Festival]] describes the film as \"..''a fable of women\u2019s suffering, inspired by Eve\u2019s \u201cforbidden apple\u201d in the Garden of Eden, and Snow White. Filmed in Saudi Arabia, it could be set anywhere in the world today, with its urgent and all-too-timely message about the cycle of abuse against women \u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BlIybkoHmUK/|title=TIFF on Instagram: \u201cMaha Al-Saati (@elosnest)\u2019s brilliant EAT ME: CYCLE OF APPLES is a fable of women\u2019s suffering, inspired by Eve\u2019s \u201cforbidden apple\u201d in the\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.\n\n=== A Trip to Disney (Work in progress) ===\nAl-Saati's feature film project \"A Trip to Disney\" is in development with the Red Sea Film Lodge (part of Saudi Arabia's [[Red Sea International Film Festival]]), in partnership with Italy's [[TorinoFilmLab]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.torinofilmlab.it/news/640-announcing-the-12-selected-projects-for-the-red-sea-lodge-2019|title=Announcing the 12 selected projects for the Red Sea Lodge 2019! {{!}} TorinoFilmLab|website=www.torinofilmlab.it|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>''.'' She is one of the female directors that account for one-third of the 12 selected for the Red Sea Lodge, the festival said<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/saudis-red-sea-international-film-festival-unveils-debut-lab-selection/5143374.article|title=Saudi's Red Sea International Film Festival unveils debut lab selection|last=Goodfellow2019-10-01T15:55:00+01:00|first=Melanie|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. ''\"The new project is about a Saudi woman who, abandoned by her lover, travels from Saudi Arabia to Florida. \u201cFinding herself in the Disney empire,\u201d presumably at Disney World in Orlando, the film\u2019s protagonist \u201cdiscovers she is not his princess,\u201d reads the synopsis. Saudi women up until last month were not allowed to travel abroad without permission from a male \u201cguardian\u201d'', [[Variety (magazine)]] says<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/saudi-arabia-red-sea-festival-projects-in-development-1203353478/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Red Sea Festival Announces Projects in Development|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2019-10-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>.\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Film Title\n!Arabic Title\n!Year\n!Type\n!Screenings\n!Nominations\n|-\n|Elo's Nest\n|\u0639\u0634 \u0625\u064a\u0644\u0648\n|2016\n|short film\n|The 3rd Saudi Film Festival, [[Bare Bones International Film Festival]]\n|\n|-\n|Fear: Audibly\n|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0648\u0641: \u0635\u0648\u062a\u064a\u0627\n|2017\n|short film\n|[[Fantastic Fest]], The Arab Cinema Festival at the [[Arab World Institute]] in Paris, The 4th Saudi Film Festival\n|\n|-\n|Hair: The Story of Grass\n|\u0634\u0639\u0631: \u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0639\u0634\u0628\n|2018\n|short film\n|[[Fantastic Fest]], [[Slamdance Film Festival]], [[HollyShorts Film Festival]], [[Red Sea International Film Festival]], The Arab Film Festival of the [[Arab American National Museum]], The 5th Saudi Film Festival, [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival, Casablana Film Festival.\n|Nominated for the NewFilmmakers Los Angeles 2020 Best of NFMLA Awards in the Best International Short Film, Drama category\n|-\n|E-pidemic\n|\u0622\u0641\u0629 \u0625\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0631\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0629\n|2018\n|short film\n|[[Middle East Broadcasting Center]] Channel / AramTV - Qomrah 3 Show\n|\n|-\n|Cycle of Apples\n|\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u062a\u0641\u0627\u062d\n|2019\n|short film\n|The14th Mizna Twin Cities Arab Film Festival, 10th Oaxaca FilmFest, 25th SPE Media Festival 2020, [[Beirut International Women Film Festival]] (BWFF), The New Filmmakers LA Film festival hosted by The [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]],  [[Society for Photographic Education|SPE]] Media Festival.\n|\n|-\n|A Trip to Disney (working title)\n|\u0631\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u062f\u064a\u0632\u0646\u064a\n|In-Development\n|feature\n|In-Development with The [[Red Sea International Film Festival]], in partnership with Italy's [[TorinoFilmLab]]<ref name=\":0\" />''.'' \n|\n|}\n\n== Research ==\nAl-Saati holds a Bachelors degree in Interior Design and a Masters degree in Architecture from King Faisal University, Saudi Arabia<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA336&lpg=PA336&dq=maha+al-saati+king+faisal+university&source=bl&ots=wXoRjpI-BJ&sig=ACfU3U1p-09x0U5pX6Hhp0JO3FSHGROGlw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjC_4KTkfToAhX4SBUIHV0nCY8Q6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20king%20faisal%20university&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref>.  She also has a PhD in Interactive Arts and Technology, from [[Simon Fraser University]] (SFU), [[Surrey, British Columbia]], [[Canada]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA282&lpg=PA282&dq=maha+zeini+al-saati&source=bl&ots=EO8_LSmG5c&sig=ACfU3U1P-X0pBuyt6e8pu5_k0IvTiyb_bA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsqoT_vfLnAhVfRhUIHV6ACMkQ6AEwCXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20zeini%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis|title=The architectural image: space, movement and myth|url=https://summit.sfu.ca/item/13638|publisher=Communication, Art & Technology: School of Interactive Arts and Technology|date=2013-07-22|degree=Thesis|language=en|first=Maha Zeini|last=Al-Saati}}</ref>. Her PhD thesis is titled: ''\"The Architectural Image: Space, Movement and Myth\"'' (2013), which was supervised by Dr. [[Robert Woodbury (athlete)|Robert Woodbury]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Saati|first=Maha Zeini|title=The Architectural Image: Space, Movement and Myth|url=https://www.academia.edu/7577363/The_Architectural_Image_Space_Movement_and_Myth|journal=PhD Thesis, The School of Interactive Arts and Technology, Simon Fraser University (SFU), Canada.|language=en}}</ref>, and falls within research that intersects architecture with film<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00a0Al-Saati, Maha Zeini; David Botta and Robert Woodbury|first=|date=|title=Moving in filmic spaces: Relating camera movements to spatial archetypes in architectural animations|url=http://papers.cumincad.org/cgi-bin/works/paper/caadria2012_013|journal=Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on Computer Aided Architectural Design Research in Asia|volume=|pages=Chennai 25-28 April 2012|via=Chennai 25-28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Saati|first=Maha Zeini; David Botta and Robert Woodbury|date=2012|title=Architects on architectural film and animation|url=http://papers.cumincad.org/cgi-bin/works/Show?caadria2012_021|journal=Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on Computer Aided Architectural Design Research in Asia / Chennai 25-28 April 2012, pp. 637\u2013646|publisher=CUMINCAD}}</ref>. She is also a researcher who has written about the intersection of media, religion and culture<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA282&lpg=PA282&dq=maha+zeini+al-saati&source=bl&ots=EO8_LSmG5c&sig=ACfU3U1P-X0pBuyt6e8pu5_k0IvTiyb_bA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsqoT_vfLnAhVfRhUIHV6ACMkQ6AEwCXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=maha%20zeini%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref> in her works: ''\u201cThe Protagonist Does Not Die Anymore: The Influence of the Death Narrative on Popular Saudi Culture\u201d''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teodorescu|first=Adriana|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=u2iPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR6&dq=maha+al-saati+Death+within+the+Text:+Social,+Philosophical+and+Aesthetic+Approaches+to+Literature,+edited+by+Adriana+Teodorescu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjR_IOF-vHnAhXMA2MBHThHAh4Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=Death within the Text: Social, Philosophical and Aesthetic Approaches to Literature|date=2019-03-13|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-3122-2|language=en}}</ref>''; \"A Question of Relevance: Teaching with Sci-Fi and Fantasy Film in a Saudi University\"''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janak|first=Edward A.|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?hl=en&lr=&id=WFYYDgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=maha+al-saati+protagonist&ots=wXoMqhB1uD&sig=kTJk98HExkxXU4A4XwYp5qymoSE&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati%20protagonist&f=false|title=Educating through Popular Culture: You're Not Cool Just Because You Teach with Comics|last2=Sourdot|first2=Ludovic A.|date=2017-03-01|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-4918-9|language=en}}</ref>; and the journal article ''\"Assassin's Creed : A Multi-Cultural Read\"''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seif El-Nasr|first=Magy|last2=Al-Saati|first2=Maha|last3=Niedenthal|first3=Simon|last4=Milam|first4=David|date=2008|title=Assassin's Creed : A Multi-Cultural Read|url=http://muep.mau.se/handle/2043/12753|journal=Loading . . .;3|volume=2|issn=1923-2691}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Winston|first=Diane|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=MCCja27G0AAC&pg=PA241&lpg=PA241&dq=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Religion+and+the+American+News+Media+maha+al-saati&source=bl&ots=JTS1BfUQdE&sig=ACfU3U31GPn0jUDaYQ3aOw3tSyCpOR2j2g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn08azl_TnAhVz8uAKHax6A8cQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20Oxford%20Handbook%20of%20Religion%20and%20the%20American%20News%20Media%20maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of Religion and the American News Media|date=2012-09-06|publisher=OUP USA|isbn=978-0-19-539506-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Young|first=Helen|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=eCg_CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT207&dq=maha+al-saati&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSoZjQl_TnAhVFA2MBHXxmBrsQ6AEIQTAD#v=onepage&q=maha%20al-saati&f=false|title=The Middle Ages in Popular Culture: Medievalism and Genre|date=2015-07-08|publisher=Cambria Press|isbn=978-1-62196-748-4|language=en}}</ref>. French author Lily Valette covers her short film Hair: The Story of Grass in her book ''\u201cDans le sens du poil arabe\" (2020) [English: In the Direction of Arab Hair]'' which compares the social attitudes towards body hair in Arab versus Western culture<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.lalibrairie.com/livres/le-poil-arabe_0-6236267_9791093315171.html|title=Livre : Dans le sens du poil arabe \u00e9crit par Maha Al-Saati et Lily Valette - Orients|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culture.leclerc/livre-u/arts-culture--societe-u/sciences-humaines-u/ethnologie-u/le-poil-arabe-9791093315171-pr|title=Dans le sens du poil arabe|last=E.Leclerc|first=Dans le sens du poil arabe-Lily Valette- 9791093315171- Espace Culturel|website=Espace Culturel E. Leclerc|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gibert.com/le-poil-arabe-11464541.html|title=Ldans le sens du poil arabe|website=www.gibert.com|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8242195}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{morecat|date=April 2020|Categories=}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Al-Saati, Maha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Arab film directors]]\n[[Category:Simon Fraser University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Canadian experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Canada-film-director-stub}}\n", "name_user": "IndieSaudiFilm", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maha_Al-Saati"}
