{"title_page": "Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion", "text_new": "{{coord|42|20|55|N|71|02|10|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=title}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion\n| fullname               = \n| former names           = Harborlights Pavilion {{small|(1994-98)}}<br>BankBoston Pavilion {{small|(1999)}}<br>FleetBoston Pavilion {{small|(2000-04)}}<br>Bank of America Pavilion {{small|(2004-13)}}<br>Blue Hills Bank Pavilion {{small|(2014-19)}}\n| logo_image             = \n| logo_caption           = \n| image                  = File:2017 Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion from Boston Harbor.jpg\n| image_size             = 250px\n| image_alt              = \n| caption                = from Boston Harbor (2017)\n| address                = 290 Northern Ave<br>[[Boston]], [[Massachusetts|MA]] 02210-2016\n| location               = [[South Boston|Seaport District]]\n| broke_ground           = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1994|08|12|}}\n| renovated              = 1998-99\n| closed                 = \n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = [[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]]\n| operator               = \n| cost                   = \n| architect              = FTL Associates\n| builder                =\n| project_manager        = \n| structural engineer    = Ross Dalland, P.E.\n| services engineer      = \n| general_contractor     = \n| main_contractors       = \n| capacity               = 5,200\n| embedded               = \n {{Infobox building\n  | embed = yes <!-- or child=yes or subbox=yes-->\n  | mapframe  = no\n  | ren_architect       = A.Form Architecture\n  | ren_engineer        = [[BuroHappold Engineering|BuroHappold]]\n  | ren_contractor      = Beacon Skanska\n  | ren_str_engineer    = Spandome Center\n  | ren_civ_engineer    = H. W. Moore Associates, Inc.\n  }}\n| website                = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| publictransit          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion''' is an outdoor [[amphitheater]] located in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. The venue originally opened August 1994 near [[Port of Boston|Fan Pier]]. Due to land rights, the venue closed at the end of its season in 1998 and was relocated to its current location in South Boston, in 1999. The relocated amphitheater opened July 1999 and seats 5,200. The venue's season runs from May until September.\n\n==Name rights==\n* '''Harborlights Pavilion''' was the original name.  It was located at the site of the current US District Courthouse at Fan Pier.  It was moved a few hundred yards down the street when the courthouse was built.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kronenburg |first= |date=1996 |title=Portable Architecture |url= |location=[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |publisher=[[Princeton Architectural Press]] |page= |isbn=0750623888|author-link= }}</ref>\n* '''Bank of Boston Pavilion'''.<ref>[http://www.bostonpavilion.net/ ''BostonPavilion.net'']</ref>\n* '''BankBoston Pavilion'''. When Bank of Boston and Baybank merged in 1996 to form [[BankBoston]], the pavilion likewise changed its name to the BankBoston Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/stories/1999/12/20/story1.html |title=BankBoston Pavilion: Good-bye South Boston? |last1=Goodison |first1=Donna L. |last2= |first2= |date=December 20, 1999 |website=[[Boston Business Journal]] |publisher=[[American City Business Journals]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''FleetBoston Pavilion'''. In 1999, [[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]] purchased the venue and sold the naming rights to [[FleetBoston Financial]], renaming the venue FleetBoston Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tech.mit.edu/V120/N29/No_Doubt_review.29a.html |title=No Doubt, Lit, Black Eyed Peas |last1=Cholankeril |first1= Eric J.|last2=Sunkavally |first2=Naveen |date=July 12, 2000 |website=[[The Tech (newspaper)|The Tech]] |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Bank of America Pavilion'''. In 2004 FleetBoston merged with [[Bank of America]] and the pavilion was then renamed to Bank of America Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/09/23/bank-america-pavilion-will-need-new-name/aIX9u6EwQNu9pRkJESnXvO/story.html |title=Seaport concert venue in search of a name |last1=Fernandes |first1=Deirdre |last2= |first2= |date=September 24, 2013 |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company|New England Media Group]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Blue Hills Bank Pavilion'''. Beginning January 1, 2014, [[Blue Hills Bank]] won the naming rights for the venue for a period of just under 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/12/14/blue-hills-bank-gets-its-name-waterfront-pavilion-blue-hills-bank-name-concert-venue/F0zKk8cEf8QuqcVNb70nyK/story.html|title=\nBlue Hills Bank gets its name on waterfront pavilion|last1=Fernandes |first1=Deirdre |last2= |first2= |date=December 14, 2013 |website=The Boston Globe |publisher=New England Media Group |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion.''' Beginning February 4, 2019, following Rockland Trust Bank's acquisition of Blue Hills Bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2019/02/04/rockland-trust-hoists-its-name-onto-seaport-concert-pavilion/RbvL3Y3QyPUB7ydnLQt7uL/story.html|title=Rockland Trust hoists its name onto Seaport concert pavilion - The Boston Globe|last=Colunist|first=Jon Chesto-|website=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Noted performers==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[311 (band)|311]]\n*[[Al Jarreau]]\n*[[The All American Rejects]]\n*[[All Time Low]]\n*[[The Allman Brothers Band]]\n*[[The Arcade Fire]]\n*[[Barenaked Ladies]] - 2010, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2018\n*[[B.B. King]]\n*[[Beck]]\n*[[Billie Eilish]]\n*[[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] - July 30, 2017 ([[Rage and Rapture Tour]])\n*[[Boney James]]\n*[[Borns]]\n*[[Britney Spears]]\n*[[Celtic Woman]] 2005, 2006\n*[[Chicago (band)|Chicago]]\n*[[Coldplay]]\n*[[Culture Club]]\n*[[Dan Fogelberg]]\n*[[Dashboard Confessional]]\n*[[David Byrne]]\n*[[Demi Lovato]] \n*[[Diana Ross]]\n*[[Don Henley]]\n*[[Elvis Costello|Elvis Costello and The Attractions]]\n*[[Extreme (band)|Extreme]]\n*[[Faith No More]]\n*[[Father John Misty]]\n*[[Fifth Harmony]]\n*[[Florence and the Machine]]\n*[[Frank Sinatra]]\n*[[Gipsy Kings]]\n*[[Gorillaz]]\n*[[Idina Menzel]]\n*[[Imagine Dragons]] \n*[[James Brown]]\n*[[Jean Michel Jarre]]\n*[[Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]\n*[[John Denver]]\n*[[Josh Groban]]\n*[[J Geils Band]]\n*[[Keane (band)|Keane]]\n*[[Lauryn Hill]]\n*[[Liza Minnelli]]\n*[[Luther Vandross]]\n*[[Mark Knopfler]]\n*[[Meghan Trainor]] - 2015, 2016\n*[[Modest Mouse]]\n*[[Nas]]\n*[[Natalie Cole]]\n*[[Night Ranger]]\n*[[Nina Simone]]\n*[[No Doubt]]\n*[[Norah Jones]]\n*[[Poison (American band)|Poison]]\n*[[Radiohead]]\n*[[Roberta Flack]]\n*[[Roxy Music]]\n*[[Ryan Adams]]\n*[[Sammy Hagar#The Circle (2014\u2013present)|Sammy Hagar and the Circle]]\n*[[Spoon (band)|Spoon]]\n*[[Steely Dan]]\n*[[Stevie Wonder]]\n*[[Sturgill Simpson]]\n*[[Styx (band)|Styx]]\n*[[Tori Amos]]\n*[[Twenty One Pilots]]\n*[[Van Morrison]]\n*[[Ween]]\n*[[Young The Giant]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Recordings==\nOn September 7, 1997, [[Widespread Panic]] recorded a version of their song \"Pickin' Up the Pieces\" with special guest [[Branford Marsalis]] for the live album ''[[Light Fuse, Get Away]]''.\n\nOn August 21, 2007, progressive metal band [[Dream Theater]] recorded three songs for their live album and DVD ''[[Chaos in Motion 2007\u20132008]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of contemporary amphitheatres]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion}}\n\n{{Live Nation}}\n{{Music venues of Massachusetts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blue Hills Bank Pavilion}}\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1994]]\n[[Category:Amphitheaters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Boston]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Boston]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{Boston-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coord|42|20|55|N|71|02|10|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=title}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion\n| fullname               = \n| former names           = Harborlights Pavilion {{small|(1994-98)}}<br>BankBoston Pavilion {{small|(1999)}}<br>FleetBoston Pavilion {{small|(2000-04)}}<br>Bank of America Pavilion {{small|(2004-13)}}<br>Blue Hills Bank Pavilion {{small|(2014-19)}}\n| logo_image             = \n| logo_caption           = \n| image                  = File:2017 Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion from Boston Harbor.jpg\n| image_size             = 250px\n| image_alt              = \n| caption                = from Boston Harbor (2017)\n| address                = 290 Northern Ave<br>[[Boston]], [[Massachusetts|MA]] 02210-2016\n| location               = [[South Boston|Seaport District]]\n| broke_ground           = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1994|08|12|}}\n| renovated              = 1998-99\n| closed                 = \n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = [[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]]\n| operator               = \n| cost                   = \n| architect              = FTL Associates\n| builder                =\n| project_manager        = \n| structural engineer    = Ross Dalland, P.E.\n| services engineer      = \n| general_contractor     = \n| main_contractors       = \n| capacity               = 5,200\n| embedded               = \n {{Infobox building\n  | embed = yes <!-- or child=yes or subbox=yes-->\n  | mapframe  = no\n  | ren_architect       = A.Form Architecture\n  | ren_engineer        = [[BuroHappold Engineering|BuroHappold]]\n  | ren_contractor      = Beacon Skanska\n  | ren_str_engineer    = Spandome Center\n  | ren_civ_engineer    = H. W. Moore Associates, Inc.\n  }}\n| website                = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| publictransit          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion''' is an outdoor [[amphitheater]] located in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. The venue originally opened August 1994 near [[Port of Boston|Fan Pier]]. Due to land rights, the venue closed at the end of its season in 1998 and was relocated to its current location in South Boston, in 1999. The relocated amphitheater opened July 1999 and seats 5,200. The venue's season runs from May until September.\n\n==Name rights==\n* '''Harborlights Pavilion''' was the original name.  It was located at the site of the current US District Courthouse at Fan Pier.  It was moved a few hundred yards down the street when the courthouse was built.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kronenburg |first= |date=1996 |title=Portable Architecture |url= |location=[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |publisher=[[Princeton Architectural Press]] |page= |isbn=0750623888|author-link= }}</ref>\n* '''Bank of Boston Pavilion'''.<ref>[http://www.bostonpavilion.net/ ''BostonPavilion.net'']</ref>\n* '''BankBoston Pavilion'''. When Bank of Boston and Baybank merged in 1996 to form [[BankBoston]], the pavilion likewise changed its name to the BankBoston Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/stories/1999/12/20/story1.html |title=BankBoston Pavilion: Good-bye South Boston? |last1=Goodison |first1=Donna L. |last2= |first2= |date=December 20, 1999 |website=[[Boston Business Journal]] |publisher=[[American City Business Journals]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''FleetBoston Pavilion'''. In 1999, [[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]] purchased the venue and sold the naming rights to [[FleetBoston Financial]], renaming the venue FleetBoston Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tech.mit.edu/V120/N29/No_Doubt_review.29a.html |title=No Doubt, Lit, Black Eyed Peas |last1=Cholankeril |first1= Eric J.|last2=Sunkavally |first2=Naveen |date=July 12, 2000 |website=[[The Tech (newspaper)|The Tech]] |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Bank of America Pavilion'''. In 2004 FleetBoston merged with [[Bank of America]] and the pavilion was then renamed to Bank of America Pavilion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/09/23/bank-america-pavilion-will-need-new-name/aIX9u6EwQNu9pRkJESnXvO/story.html |title=Seaport concert venue in search of a name |last1=Fernandes |first1=Deirdre |last2= |first2= |date=September 24, 2013 |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company|New England Media Group]] |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Blue Hills Bank Pavilion'''. Beginning January 1, 2014, [[Blue Hills Bank]] won the naming rights for the venue for a period of just under 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/12/14/blue-hills-bank-gets-its-name-waterfront-pavilion-blue-hills-bank-name-concert-venue/F0zKk8cEf8QuqcVNb70nyK/story.html|title=\nBlue Hills Bank gets its name on waterfront pavilion|last1=Fernandes |first1=Deirdre |last2= |first2= |date=December 14, 2013 |website=The Boston Globe |publisher=New England Media Group |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''Rockland Trust Bank Pavilion.''' Beginning February 4, 2019, following Rockland Trust Bank's acquisition of Blue Hills Bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2019/02/04/rockland-trust-hoists-its-name-onto-seaport-concert-pavilion/RbvL3Y3QyPUB7ydnLQt7uL/story.html|title=Rockland Trust hoists its name onto Seaport concert pavilion - The Boston Globe|last=Colunist|first=Jon Chesto-|website=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Noted performers==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[311 (band)|311]]\n*[[Al Jarreau]]\n*[[The All American Rejects]]\n*[[All Time Low]]\n*[[The Allman Brothers Band]]\n*[[The Arcade Fire]]\n*[[Barenaked Ladies]] - 2010, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2018\n*[[B.B. King]]\n*[[Beck]]\n*[[Billie Eilish]]\n*[[Boney James]]\n*[[Borns]]\n*[